[{"id":32418,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p>b</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p>c</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p>a</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","d"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Micelles are formed&nbsp;by self-assembly of&nbsp;amphiphilic&nbsp;molecules. The structures contain hydrophilic/polar region (head) and hydrophobic/nonpolar region (tail). Micelles are formed in aqueous solution whereby the polar region faces the outside surface of the micelle and the nonpolar region forms the core.</p><p>Non-polar part will interact with non-polar solvent.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/632349ec-a238-42d7-9c30-8652e7f4aa91-9896087_A.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 200px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32457,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ba</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>PO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The ion which is&nbsp;responsible for neutralization of charge<b> on</b>&nbsp;the colloidal particles is called the coagulating ion or Flocculating ion. So, according to this rule, greater the charge on an oppositely charged ion, greater is its coagulation power.</p><p>To coagulate negative sol, cation with higher charge has higher coagulation value.</p><p>So answer is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ba</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32450,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is not the<br />correct explanation fo <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are correct and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is the correct<br />explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is not correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is correct.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is not correct."],"answer":1,"solution":"Gases having higher critical temperatures have greater extent of intermolecular force of attractions and those gases readily adsorb on the activated charcoal.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32446,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["the colloidal particles have no charge.","the colloidal particles have positive charge.","the colloidal particles are solvated.","there is a strong electrostatic repulsion between the negatively charged colloidal particles."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Lyophilic sols are quite stable and cannot be easily coagulated. Lyophobic sols need stabilising agents for their preservation.</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Property</td>\t\t\t<td>Lyophilic colloids</td>\t\t\t<td>Lyophobic colloids</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Stability</td>\t\t\t<td>These are very stable</td>\t\t\t<td>These are unstable and require traces of stabilizers</td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32410,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The coagulating power of an electrolyte is a measure of its ability to cause the coagulation or precipitation of a colloidal solution.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Coagulation</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>power</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>Coagulation</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>value</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>&nbsp;Coagulating value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>As</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>09</mn></math><br />&nbsp;Coagulating value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi></math> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>As</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn></math></p><p>Then,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi>NaCl</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi>NaCl</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>09</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>50</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi>NaCl</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>556</mn><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi>NaCl</mi></msub></math><br />&nbsp; So the answer is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>556</mn><mo>.</mo></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32445,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7e009b02-c324-4d15-871b-d87752e7b15f-image.png\" style=\"width: 225px; height: 160px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fb2ec480-7ec8-439e-b30a-de74bbb903e5-image.png\" style=\"width: 220px; height: 153px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b2543e8d-2815-4579-b421-c4f0c03c8791-image.png\" style=\"width: 225px; height: 159px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f4bec706-f560-405f-9f80-97292038e59b-image.png\" style=\"width: 225px; height: 163px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"On increase in temperature <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>m</mi></mfrac></mfenced></math> decreases.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32500,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Gelatin","Starch","Oleate","Gum Arabic"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br />It is defined as the minimum amount of protective colloid in milligrams which prevents a colour change from red to violet of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math>&nbsp;gold solution by the addition of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math>&nbsp;of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>NaCl</mi></math>&nbsp;Solution.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32428,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Freundlich, in 1909, gave an empirical relationship between the quantity of gas adsorbed by unit mass of solid adsorbent and pressure at a particular temperature. The relationship can be expressed by the following equation</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>KP</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></msup></math></p><p>Where x is the mass of the gas adsorbed on mass m of the adsorbent at pressure P, k and n are constants which depend on the nature of the adsorbent and the gas at a particular temperature. The relationship is generally represented in the form of a curve where mass of the gas adsorbed per gram of the adsorbent is plotted against pressure.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mi>logp</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>logk</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/19955060-2d70-489c-92ba-810167c915d6-image.png\" style=\"width: 193px; height: 170px;\" /></p><p>Freundlich isotherm explains the behaviour of adsorption in an approximate manner. The factor <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></math> can have values between 0 and 1</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32523,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["magnesium chloride solution coagulates, the gold sol more readily than the iron (III) hydroxide sol.","sodium sulphate solution causes coagulation in both sols","mixing the sols has no effect","coagulation in both sols can be brought about by electrophoresis"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":32458,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["solid sol","gel","aerosol","foam"],"answer":0,"solution":"Colloid of gas dispersed in solid is called solid sol. Foam, Rubber are some examples of this type of sol.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32412,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p>A, C, D only</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p>A, B only</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p>B, C, D only</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p>A, B, D only</p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The equation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>KP</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;represents Freundlich adsorption isotherm. It is an empirical relationship between the amount of gas adsorbed by a given amount of solid adsorbent surface and pressure of the gas at a particular temperature.</p><p>So, Freundlich adsorption isotherm equation is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>KP</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>logK</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mi>logP</mi></math></p><p>Extent of adsorption&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac></mfenced></math>&nbsp;decreases with increase in temperature.</p><p>With the help of the above two equation, following plots are obtained</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7ce9c9db-d3dc-43ee-9116-350e911e95d7.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 195px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6dfb9cd5-1282-45a2-849d-38f839b0aa46.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 166px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5097b1b8-eb8f-4346-98b9-d81285774e92.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 196px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32422,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Surface tension is the outcome of unequal attractive and repulsion forces acting on the liquid molecule in bulk. Surface tension is due to uneven forces acting on the molecules present on the surface.&nbsp;The molecule in the bulk can&nbsp;come to the liquid surface- due to brownian movement and convection. The molecules on the surface are responsible for vapour pressure if the system is a closed system.</p><p>Thus, B and D options are correct.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32518,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["It occurs because of vander Waal's forces.","More easily liquefiable gases are adsorbed readily.","Under high pressure it results into multi molecular layer on adsorbent surface.","Enthalpy of adsorption $\\left(\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_{\\text {adsorption }}\\right)$ is low and positive."],"answer":3,"solution":"Enthalpy of adsorption regarding physissorption is not positive and it is negative.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":32414,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The Zymase enzyme converts glucose and fructose into ethanol and carbon dioxide. And the Invertase enzyme is used to convert sucrose or cane sugar into glucose and fructose. The enzyme diastase&nbsp;converts starch to maltose. The enzyme pepsin converts proteins to amino acids.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32451,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Freundlich isotherm. ;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mo>&#183;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></msup></math><br />Substituting values ; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mfrac><mn>64</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>166</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8773;</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32474,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Ostwald process","Van Arkel Method","Bredig&#39;s Arc Method","Mond Process"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Bredig&rsquo;s Arc Method is used for preparation of colloidal sol&rsquo;s of less reactive metal like Au, Ag, Pt.</p><p>Ostwald process is used for preparation of nitric acid.</p><p>Van Arkel method is used&nbsp;for refining Zirconium or Titanium.</p><p>The&nbsp;Mond process&nbsp;is a method for refining nickel. The nickel oxide and impurities react with the hydrogen gas to form an impure solid nickel.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32435,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Colloidal particles always carry an electric charge. The nature of this charge is the same on all the particles in a given colloidal solution and may be either positive or negative.&nbsp;</p><p>Negatively charged sol&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>CdS</mi></math></p><p>Positively charged&nbsp;sol&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>.</mo><msub><mi>xH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>Macromolecular colloids are&nbsp;individual particles that are large enough to be considered colloids&nbsp;(diameter around 100 nm). These particles are made up of chemicals with a high molecular weight.</p><p>Macromolecular colloid&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>Starch</p><p>Gel&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>&nbsp;Cheese</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32452,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Cheese <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> liquid in solid<br />Pumice stone <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> gas in solid Hair cream <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> liquid in liquid<br />Cloud <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> liquid in gas","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32491,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>→</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>In&nbsp;chromatography;</p><p>Benzaldehyde is a substance that is absorbed. It acts as an adsorbate.</p><p>Benzaldehyde:- Adsorbate</p><p>Alumina is a highly porous substance that adsorbs another substance. It acts as an adsorbent.</p><p>Alumina:- adsorbent</p><p>Acetonitrile is used as a mobile phase in chromatography.</p><p>Acetonitrile:- mobile phase</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32478,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["They are larger than small molecules and have high molar mass.","They can scatter lighht.","The osmotic pressure of a collodial solution is of higher order than the true solution at the same concentration.","The range of diameters of colloidal particles is between <math><mn>1</mn></math> and <math><mn>1000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>.</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Due to the bigger size of colloidal particles the number of particles in a colloidal solution is comparatively small as compared to a true solution. Hence the values of colligative properties are of small order as compared to values shown by true solutions at same concentration.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32448,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> added to KI solution","KI added to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> solution","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mi>x</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> in water","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> added to hot water"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> added to hot water,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f871cf71-2160-4f97-887f-fdf0586564c4-ed09eacc-f2af-4159-82b3-d6dcf7194d01-ce117026-f239-4d9f-ab92-f4ead34eb900-image.png\" style=\"width: 247px; height: 70px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math> When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is added to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KI</mi></math>,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/69844817-e584-4c02-847e-a8648856e519-6c58a644-135b-4f7d-adc5-316564256e7b-5d1f7c1c-f6de-42a6-a0f3-820a4f4ecc20-image.png\" style=\"width: 354px; height: 70px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></math> When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Kl</mi></math> is added to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/485c1447-1e80-431b-b9d9-1305979369e2-aef35db5-521b-4c7d-a906-fd6a760fd855-4966b658-fc7d-47e8-a9c4-7f59165b9bd2-image.png\" style=\"width: 383px; height: 69px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>4</mn></mfenced><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> in water&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>Al</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;positively charged&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32473,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["(d) and (a)&nbsp;","(b) and (c)","(a) and (b)","(c) and (d)"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>(a) When gas is adsorbed on metal surface.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> become less negative with progress of reaction because number of active sites decreases.<br />(b) Gas with greater value of critical temperature <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></mfenced></math> absorbed more. As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced></math> So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> absorbed more than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p><p>Statement (c) is wrong because residual forces decrease as adsorption proceeds further.</p><p>Statement (d) is also wrong because temperature opposes extent of adsorption.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32516,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["$x / m$ vs $p$","$x / m$ vs $1 / p$","$\\log x / m$ vs $\\log p$","$\\log x / m$ vs $p$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Freundlich adsorption isotherm gives straight line on plotting $\\log x / m$ vs $\\log p$ as show below.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/98bQQbgB4UJhbDA78S2k5hlHd7NKZ4Jzatl1hYF6wlA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":32498,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["sols of metal sulphides are lyophilic.","Brownian movement is more pronounced for smaller particles than for bigger-particles.","one would expect charcoal to adsorb chlorine more than hydrogen sulphide.","Hardy Schulze law states that bigger the size of the ions, the greater is its coagulating power."],"answer":1,"solution":"Brownian movement is the random motion of particles suspended in a fluid (liquid or gas), resulting from their collision with the fast moving atom or molecules in the liquid or gaseous state of the matter. That means, smaller particles are responsible for the Brownian movement.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32441,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Mole of acetic acid absorbed (on 0.6 gram charcoal) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>200</mn><mo>)</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8211;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>)</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace></math></p><p>Weight of CH<sub>3</sub>COOH absorbed (on 0.6 gram charcoal)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gram</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gram</mi></math></p><p>Mass of CH<sub>3</sub>COOH absorbed per gram=<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>grams</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32475,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ebd303be-dbd5-4be7-b1ef-55b86665ec9a-image.png\" style=\"width: 298px; height: 230px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><mfenced><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>m</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>P</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>m</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>log</mi><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mi>log</mi><mi>P</mi></math></p><p>Slope&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Intercept ,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mi>k</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>477</mn></math> So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>log</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>477</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p><p>so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>m</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>P</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>[</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mo>]</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>48</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32434,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Brownian motion destabilises sols.","Any amount of dispersed phase can be added to emulsion without destabilising it.","Mixing two oppositely charged sols in equal amount neutralises charges and stabilises colloids.","Presence of equal and similar charges on colloidal particles provides stability to the colloidal solution."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>As equal &amp; similar charge particle will repel each other, hence will never precipitate. So, the option D is correct.</p><p>Mixing two oppositely charged sols in equal amount neutralises charges and as a result colloids precipitate.</p><p>Only a certain&nbsp;amount of dispersed phase can be added to emulsion without destabilising it.</p><p>Brownian motion stabilises sols.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32463,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["zero","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8734;</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Freundlich gave a relation between the amount of the gas adsorbed per unit mass of the adsorbent&nbsp;(m) and the pressure (p). This is known as Freundlich&rsquo;s adsorption isotherm.</p><p>As per Freundlich adsorption isotherm</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>KP</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32449,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;H</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&#916;S</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;H</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&#916;S</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;H</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&#916;S</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;H</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&#916;S</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Adsorption is spontaneous process therefore change in free energy is negative. Adsorption of gas on solid surface is exothermic process &amp; entropy is decrease in this process so</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;H</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&#916;S</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32407,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Adsorption theory of Heterogeneous catalysis involves five steps-<ol>\t<li>Diffusion of reactants to the surface of the catalyst.</li>\t<li>Adsorption of reactant molecules on the surface of the catalyst. (Occurrence of chemical reaction on the catalyst&rsquo;s surface through formation of an intermediate.</li>\t<li>&nbsp;Desorption of reaction products from the catalyst surface&nbsp;</li>\t<li>Making the surface available again for more reaction to occur.</li>\t<li>&nbsp;Diffusion of reaction products away from the catalyst&rsquo;s surface.</li></ol>So, we can deduce from Adsorption theory of catalysis that as the concentration of reactants at active centres increases due to adsorption and thus the rate of the reaction is also increased.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null}]